SIMPLE: puncheon
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Puncheon
<hw>Punch"eon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>poin⟦cced⟧on</ets> awl, bodkin, crown, king-post, fr. L.
<ets>punctio</ets> a pricking, fr. <ets>pungere</ets> to prick. See
<er>Pungent</er>, and cf. <er>Punch</er> a tool,
<er>Punction</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A figured stamp, die, or punch, used by goldsmiths,
cutlers, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>A short, upright piece of timber
in framing; a short post; an intermediate stud.</def> <rj><au>Oxf.
Gloss.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A split log or heavy slab with the face smoothed;
<as>as, a floor made of <ex>puncheons</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark> <rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[F. <ets>poin⟦cced⟧on</ets>, perh. the same as
<ets>poin⟦cced⟧on</ets> an awl.]</ety> <def>A cask containing, sometimes
84, sometimes 120, gallons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puncher</ent>⟦br⟧
